Read the input in the order it is written.  A simple, robust way is: 

```java
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
int N = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());          // first line
int K = Integer.parseInt(br.readLine().trim());          // second line
for (int i = 0; i < K; ++i) {
    String[] parts = br.readLine().trim().split(" ");
    int x = Integer.parseInt(parts[0]);
    int y = Integer.parseInt(parts[1]);
    // … compute answer …
}
```

This guarantees that **N** and **K** are read correctly and that each query line is processed independently.

The recursion in `findValue` (and the more readable `findValue2`) expects **1‑based** coordinates.  The base case for `n == 2` is correct – only `(2, 2)` is a ‘1’.  If you prefer a cleaner mapping, use the version that subtracts `n/2` instead of `Math.abs`: 

```java
if (x <= n/2 && y <= n/2) return findValue2(n/2, x, y);
else if (x <= n/2 && y > n/2) return findValue2(n/2, x, y - n/2);
else if (x > n/2 && y <= n/2) return findValue2(n/2, x - n/2, y);
else return findValue2(n/2, x - n/2, y - n/2);
```

Both versions work, but the second one is easier to understand and less error‑prone.
